scenes.title: First icosahedral vertex
scenes.content:
Use octahedral symmetry system.
Drag B1 toward +X.
Use a custom blue length of phi.
Drag that length from the prior ball in the +Z direction.

scenes.title: All icosahedral vertices
scenes.content: Apply the tetrahedral symmetry tool in the octahedral symmetry system to generate all 12 icosa vertices.

scenes.title: Remove icosa scafolding
scenes.content: Delete the two struts, the ball at their common vertex, and the origin, leaving just the icosahedron's 12 vertices.

scenes.title: Remove tridimished vertices
scenes.content: Remove the three vertices that are ot part of J63.

scenes.title: J63 convex hull
scenes.content: Select all of the balls and make a convex hull having struts only (no panels yet).

scenes.title: Midpoint of near blue strut
scenes.content:
Make a ball at the midpoint of the near blue strut.
Use a custom blue length of sqrt(2).
Drag that length from the midpoint ball in the +Z direction.

scenes.title: Vertical edge of tetrahedron
scenes.content:
Use "build with this" to set the blue length to the edge of the icosahedron.
Drag a blue strut in the +Y direction from the most recently added ball, having that length.
Generate a ball at the midpoint of that strut.
Use the midpoint and the ball at the bottom of that strut to make a translation tool to move in the -Y direction by half the length of that strut.

scenes.title: Translate tetrahedron edge
scenes.content:
Use "select collinear" on the most recently built strut to select it, its two end points and its midpoint.
Apply the translation tool created in the previous step to move it in the -Y direction.

scenes.title: Generate tetrahedron
scenes.content:
Select the most recently moved strut and the nearest (blue) edge of the icosahedren.
Make a convex hull having struts only (no panels yet).

scenes.title: Remove tetrahedron scafolding
scenes.content: Delete the strut between the midpoints of the tetrahedron's edges and the two balls at its ends.

scenes.title: Cross product of icosahedron face
scenes.content:
Select the three vertices of the icosahedron face where the tetrahedron will eventually attach to it. Select the one that's at the bottom (on the X=0 plane) first, then move counterclockwise around the triangle.
Apply the cross product tool.

scenes.title: Cross product of tetrahedron face
scenes.content:
Select the three vertices of the tetrahedron face where the icosahedron will eventually attach to it. As before, select the one that's at the bottom (on the X=0 plane) first, then move counterclockwise around the triangle.
Apply the cross product tool.

scenes.title: Hinge panels
scenes.content: Two panels are added, not as part of the construction process, but rather to clarify the purpose of the next step. The next objective is to rotate the tetrahedron around the blue strut so the two panels coincide. A linear map tool wil be used to accomplish that rotation.

scenes.title: Build linear map tool
scenes.content:
The linear map tool requires 3 struts with a common endpoint as its input or "from" vectors. It requires three more struts as it's output or "to" vectors, and it requires a ball to represent the origin of the linear map.

In this case, one of the input vectors is the same as the corresponding output vector, so we need two parallel struts of the same lengths to represent them both. One for the input vector and one for the output. 
The input and output struts are colored red, green and blue where the input struts and their corresponding output struts are the same color. The origin of the linear mapping is the black ball originally shared by the two cross product struts.

The red and green input struts are translated to the far side of the icosahedron so they will share a vertex with the parallel blue input strut.

The three input "from" vectors (in order) are the red, green and blue struts having a white ball at their common vertex. The green and blue are parallel to the edges of the tetrahedron's face that we want to rotate, and the red is the "cross product" strut that is normal to that same tetrahedron's face.

The three output "to" vectors are selected in the same order. They are the red, green and blue struts with a black ball at their common vertex. The green and blue output struts are on the icosahedron's face onto which we want to rotate. The red output strut is the "cross product" strut that is normal to that same icosahedron's face.

scenes.title: Rotate tetrahedron into place
scenes.content: Select the edges, vertices abd face of the tetrahedron and apply the linear map tool to rotate it into place.

scenes.title: Remove linear map scaffolding
scenes.content: Remove the extra struts that weer used to generate the linear map.

scenes.title: Edges
scenes.content: Remove the internal triangular panel and reset the strut colors.

scenes.title: Faces
scenes.content: Select all, apply a 3D convex hull, delete all balls and struts. Color the panels to match the Johnson solids web site.
